To run the jobs manually:

set variables 
$VO_SUPPORT_TOOLS, $LFC_HOST

------------------------------------------------
To run the jobs in cron:

1. Install cron jobs

1.1. Use script list-users-voms.sh to generate file voms-users.txt. That file must be passed to scan-se.sh with the option --voms-users. Typically, this file should be generated with a cron like:
# Refresh the list of users from the VOMS every day
0 1 * * * . /etc/profile; export VO_SUPPORT_TOOLS=$HOME/biomed-support-tools; $VO_SUPPORT_TOOLS/SE/scan-se/list-users-voms.sh --vo biomed --voms-host voms-biomed.in2p3.fr --voms-port 8443 --out /tmp/biomed/monitor-se/voms-users.txt > /tmp/biomed/monitor-se/voms-users.log

1.2. Use script $VO_SUPPORT_TOOLS/renew-proxy.sh to renew your proxy certificate regularly:
# Renew the proxy certificate every 8 hours
0 0,8,16 * * * /path/biomed-support-tools/renew-proxy.sh 2>&1 >> /tmp/biomed/monitor-se/renew-proxy.log

2. Run the scan-se.sh script, possibly using a cron, this example runs it once a week on Sundays:
# Monitor the SEs over 80% full and get the list of users with over 100 MB
0 2 * * 0 . /etc/profile; export LFC_HOST=lfc-biomed.in2p3.fr; export VO_SUPPORT_TOOLS=$HOME/biomed-support-tools; $VO_SUPPORT_TOOLS/SE/scan-se/scan-se.sh --vo biomed --voms-users /tmp/monitor-se/voms-users.txt --work-dir /tmp/monitor-se --result-dir $HOME/public_html/scan-se --threshold 80 --user-min-used 0.1 >> /tmp/biomed/monitor-se/scan-se.log

This will use the following:
- parse-show-se-space.awk.tpl: template of awk file to filter the output of tool show-se-space.sh 
- parse-lfcbrowsese.awk.tpl: template of awk file to filter the output of LFCBrowseSE with users over a given used space
- se-heavy-user.sh: run the LFCBrowseSE tools, get the list of users over 100 MB
  - parse-lfcbrowsese.awk: process the result of LFCBrosweSE --summary
  - email-users.sh: convert the output of se-heavy-users.sh into +/- an email body

3. Optionally, once all SE have been analyzed, use script unknown-users.sh to build a consolidated list of users who have files on SEs but are no longer known in the VOMS server. E.g.:
   $VO_SUPPORT_TOOLS/SE/scan-se/unknown-users.sh --vo biomed --input-dir /tmp/biomed/monitor-se/20120104-165852

